{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019SRzRy1D5Jy62wkeagMjDg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test has `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"` as the first line. With my change, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` is checked first. \"Smażona\" - let me check if it matches the regex.\n\nThe regex has `sma[zż]` - \"Smażona\" starts with \"Smaż\" which matches `smaż` (case insensitive due to `/i` flag). Then it checks `\\b` - in \"Smażona\", after \"smaż\" comes \"o\" which is a word character, so `\\b` (word boundary) won't match here.\n\n\nActually, I need to reconsider this. The regex pattern checks for `sma[zż]` followed by a word boundary, but \"Smażona\" has \"o\" immediately after \"Smaż\", which is a word character, so the boundary condition fails and the pattern doesn't match.\n\nWait, I'm confusing myself. Let me trace through this properly: `ż` isn't recognized as a word character in JavaScript regex (which only includes `[a-zA-Z0-9_]`), so it counts as a non-word character. That means there IS a word boundary between the non-word `ż` and the word character `o` in \"Smażona\". So the pattern DOES match, and that's the actual bug—the word boundary fires at the wrong place because Polish diacritics aren't treated as word characters.\n\nTo fix this, I could use a negative lookahead to prevent matching when followed by a letter, ensuring \"Smażona\" doesn't trigger the regex... I see the issue now—the `\\b` word boundary at the end of the alternation applies to all the alternatives, so it's checking that whatever matches isn't followed by a word character. Since Polish letters like `ż` aren't recognized as word characters by JavaScript's `\\b`, the pattern incorrectly matches \"smażo\" when it shouldn't. I need to replace the word boundary with an explicit negative lookahead that includes all Polish characters to properly prevent partial matches. The simplest approach is to replace the `\\b` at the end with a negative lookahead that checks for any letter character, including Polish ones like `ą`, `ć`, `ę`, `ł`, `ń`, `ó`, `ś`, `ź`, `ż`. This way, the pattern won't incorrectly match when a non-ASCII character follows. I need to reconsider this approach—the task description explicitly stated that `Smażona` shouldn't match, only the bare `Smaż` form should. My analysis was off about how JavaScript handles word boundaries with Polish characters. The real fix is to replace `\\b` with a negative lookahead that explicitly excludes Polish letters: `(?![a-zA-ZąćęłńóśźżĄĆĘŁŃÓŚŹŻ])`. Let me review the full regex pattern to apply this correctly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":840,"cache_read_input_tokens":25923,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":840},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4407852d-7747-4d05-8f35-a479d23762b1","uuid":"a2b174b9-b75e-44ff-a96e-dc7848662e40"}
