{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DmdCJAiaTTza52sA9BsLKq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that `\\b` in JS regex doesn't understand Unicode characters. When a Polish character like `ż` is the last character of the matched alternative (e.g., `sma[zż]`), and the next character in the text is a word char like `o` (from \"smażona\"), `\\b` fires at the boundary between `ż` (non-`\\w`) and `o` (`\\w`).\n\nI need to replace `\\b` at the end of the regex with a Unicode-aware alternative. The simplest is to use a negative lookahead for any letter (including Polish letters):\n\n`(?![a-zA-ZąćęłńóśźżĄĆĘŁŃÓŚŹŻ])`\n\n\nNow I'm swapping out that `\\b` at the end of the pattern with the lookahead that explicitly checks for Polish letters, so the regex becomes `(?![a-zA-ZąćęłńóśźżĄĆĘŁŃÓŚŹŻ])/i` instead of `)\\b/i`.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2847,"cache_read_input_tokens":26763,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2847},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4407852d-7747-4d05-8f35-a479d23762b1","uuid":"ab25ddab-5ba6-4861-ba5b-950997b9e269"}
