{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Xb6UWUdMXFDdQe1VAhJFSF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that `/^DLA\\s+\\S+\\s+OSOB/i` should match \"DLA & OSOB\", but \"DLA & OSOB\" has only one token between DLA and OSOB. Let me count the characters: `DLA` + ` ` + `&` + ` ` + `OSOB`. So `\\S+` matches `&` and `\\s+` matches ` ` and then `OSOB` matches `OSOB`. That should work!\n\nWait, let me re-examine the test input. The test text has:\n```\n\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"\n\n\n\"DLA & OSOB\"\n\"200g fasolki\"\n\"1 cebula\"\n```\n\nSo \"DLA & OSOB\" is the second line. And the result is \"Smażona zielona fasolka + Smażona zielona fasolka DLA & OSOB\".\n\nThis suggests that \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" is a valid candidate, and there's another candidate that's the multi-line join of \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" + \"DLA & OSOB\", which means the filter for \"DLA & OSOB\" isn't working as expected.\n\nThe issue is that the multi-line join is combining the title line with a line that should be filtered out as metadata. I think what happened is that my fix for \"Smażona\" being incorrectly filtered as a cooking instruction now allows the code to reach the multi-line join phase, where it's creating this spurious compound. The test was written expecting \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" as the result, which means it was designed to test that \"DLA & OSOB\" gets filtered as metadata, but now I'm seeing this unexpected compound candidate being generated.\n\nLet me trace through the multi-line join logic to see if there's a guard preventing it from joining with lines that should be treated as metadata.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1343,"cache_read_input_tokens":34607,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1343},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_availabl